window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"An example of an organism that exists as a colony is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Spirogyra","B":"Paramecium","C":"Euglena","D":"Volvox"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A colony is a group of organisms of the same species living closely together, usually for mutual benefit such as stronger defense or the ability to attack bigger prey. Volvox is a genus of chlorophytes, a type of green algae. It forms spherical colonies of up to 50,000 cells. They live in a variety of freshwater habitats, and were first reported by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1700. Volvox is a colonial organism that resembles a hollow ball whose wall is composed of biflagellate cells embedded in a gelatinous matrix. Therefore, Volvox is an example of an organism that exists as a colony.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Gymnosperms bear naked seeds because they lack","images":[],"options":{"A":"ovary","B":"colourful flowers","C":"pollen grains","D":"stigma"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Gymnosperms are a group of plants that produce seeds not enclosed within an ovary or fruit. These are known as 'naked seeds'. The term 'gymnosperm' comes from the Greek word gymnospermos, meaning 'naked seeds'. The seeds develop on the surface of cone scales or other structures, which are often modified to form a 'cone-like' appearance. Hence, they lack an ovary.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"DNA formation is associated with","images":[],"options":{"A":"Golgi bodies","B":"Lysosomes","C":"Mitochondria","D":"Nucleus"},"answer":"D","explanation":"DNA (Deoxyribonucleic acid) is a molecule that carries most of the genetic instructions used in the development, functioning and reproduction of all known living organisms and many viruses. DNA is located in the cell nucleus (as nuclear DNA), but a small amount of DNA can also be found in the mitochondria (as mitochondrial DNA or mtDNA). However, the formation and replication of DNA primarily occur in the nucleus, making 'Nucleus' the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Plant A was seen to appear as plant B after seven hours.  Study the diagram carefully and answer this question      The term that can be used to describe what happened to plant A after seven hours is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"wilting","B":"competition","C":"transpiration","D":"osmosis"},"answer":"A","explanation":"From the Observation of plant A and plant B after seven hour is writing. This occurs as a result of loss of water from the plant than its take in.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Plant A was seen to appear as plant B after seven hours.  Study the diagram carefully and answer this question    The environmental factors responsible for the condition in plant B are","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"low humidity and low temperature","B":"high humidity and low temperature","C":"low humidity and high temperature","D":"high humidity and high temperature"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The environment factors responsible for the condition in plant B are as a result of low humidity and high temperature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"Hydra is considered to be at a tissue level of organization of life because it","images":[],"options":{"A":"has numerous cells that perform different functions","B":"has developed organs and systems","C":"has a poorly developed nervous system","D":"reproduces by budding"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Hydra is considered to be at a tissue level of organization of life because it has numerous cells that perform different functions. This is because, in the tissue level of organization, cells of a similar type join together to perform a shared function. In Hydra, there are different types of cells that perform different functions, such as nerve cells, muscle cells, and gland cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Study the diagrams below and answer this question.      Which of the following statements about the diagrams is correct?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"They are both organs","B":"One of them is an organism","C":"They both form part of tissues","D":"They are harmful to humans"},"answer":"B","explanation":"I - Yeast  II - White blood cell  Yeast is an Organism.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"Study the diagrams below and answer this question.    A decrease in the number of II will result in","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"an increase in urine production","B":"an increase in energy production","C":"a decreased population","D":"decreased immunity"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A decrease in the number of II [white blood cell] will decreased immunity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REGULATION OF INTERNAL ENVIRONMENT (HOMEOSTASIS)","question":"Flaccidity in plants is associated with","images":[],"options":{"A":"cessation of photosynthesis","B":"wilting","C":"turgidity","D":"discoloration of leaves"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Flaccidity in plants is associated with wilting. This is because flaccidity refers to the condition where the plant cells lose water and become less rigid, causing the plant to wilt. This is different from turgidity, which is the state of being swollen due to high fluid content, and it helps to keep the plant rigid and upright.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following substances is not usually present in the urine of a healthy person?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Urea","B":"Mineral salts","C":"Glucose","D":"Water"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a healthy person, glucose is not usually present in the urine. This is because the kidneys reabsorb all the filtered glucose from the urine into the blood. If glucose is found in the urine, it can be a sign of diabetes or other health problems.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : MUSCULAR SYSTEM","question":"Muscles act in opposite directions in order to","images":[],"options":{"A":"cause a bone to move","B":"prevent dislocation at joints","C":"prevent muscle fatigue","D":"regulate bodily activities"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Muscles act in opposite direction in order to cause a bone to move. In the case of the bicep and the triceps, when the biceps  contracts the triceps relax thereby moving in opposite direction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PLANT STRUCTURE","question":"Lateral meristem in flowering plants is found in the","images":[],"options":{"A":"cortex","B":"pericycle","C":"cambium","D":"pith"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Lateral meristem is found in the cambium of flowering plants. The cambium is a type of meristem, which is a tissue in plants consisting of undifferentiated cells (meristematic cells) capable of division and giving rise to cells that can differentiate into various types of cells. The cambium is specifically responsible for the secondary growth of the plants, which increases the width of the plant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"The cells and tissues of the nose, throat, chest diaphragm and lungs form the","images":[],"options":{"A":"circulatory system","B":"respiratory system","C":"transport system","D":"digestive system"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The cells and tissues of the nose, throat, chest diaphragm and lungs form the respiratory system. The respiratory system is a biological system consisting of specific organs and structures used for gas exchange in animals and plants. The anatomy and physiology that make this happen varies greatly, depending on the size of the organism, the environment in which it lives and its evolutionary history.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"The exchange of gases between the environment and the respiratory organs of vertebrates is referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"inhalation","B":"respiration","C":"expiration","D":"breathing"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The exchange of gases between the environment and the respiratory organs of vertebrates is referred to as breathing. Breathing is the process that moves air in and out of the lungs, to allow the diffusion of oxygen and carbon dioxide to and from the external environment into and out of the blood.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REGULATION OF INTERNAL ENVIRONMENT (HOMEOSTASIS)","question":"The maintenance of a constant internal environment in an organism is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"homeostasis","B":"homoiothermy","C":"diuresis","D":"dialysis"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The maintenance of a constant internal environment in an organism is known as homeostasis. Homeostasis is the state of steady internal, physical, and chemical conditions maintained by living systems. This dynamic state of equilibrium is the condition of optimal functioning for the organism and includes many variables, such as body temperature and fluid balance, being kept within certain pre-set limits.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following organs is responsible for the production of insulin?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Spleen","B":"Adrenal gland","C":"Thyroid gland","D":"Pancreas"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Insulin is a hormone that is produced in the body. It is made by beta cells in the pancreas. Insulin's main role is to control the level of glucose, or sugar, in the body. When the level of glucose in the blood is too high, insulin is released from the pancreas into the bloodstream. It then helps glucose to enter the cells of the body where it can be used for energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following actions is not a voluntary action?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Stealing","B":"Sneezing","C":"Fighting","D":"Cheating"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Voluntary actions are those that we choose to do and have control over. They are governed by the somatic nervous system and include actions like walking, talking, and eating. Involuntary actions, on the other hand, are those that happen without us having to think about them. They are controlled by the autonomic nervous system and include actions like heart beating, breathing, and sneezing. Sneezing is an involuntary action because it is an automatic response to irritation in the nasal passages.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PLANT STRUCTURE","question":"In both dicotyledonous and monocotyledonous plants, the root hairs originate from the","images":[],"options":{"A":"piliferous layer","B":"epidermal layer","C":"endodermal layer","D":"cortical layer"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Root hairs originate from the piliferous layer, also known as the root hair zone. This is a region of the root where cells differentiate into specialized root hair cells. These cells are elongated and thin-walled, and they increase the surface area of the root for absorption of water and minerals.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Which of the following parts of the ear does not contain endolymph?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Semi-circular canals","B":"Utriculus","C":"Tympanum","D":"Sacculus"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The tympanum, also known as the eardrum, does not contain endolymph. Endolymph is a fluid that fills the inner ear and allows us to hear and maintain balance. It is found in the cochlea and the vestibular system, which includes the semi-circular canals, utriculus, and sacculus. The tympanum, on the other hand, is a thin membrane that separates the outer ear from the middle ear and vibrates in response to sound waves.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"The type of placentation illustrated in the diagram below is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"marginal","B":"parietal","C":"axile","D":"basal"},"answer":"D","explanation":"This type of placentation is called Basal. Basal placentation is a type of placentation in flowering plants where the ovules are attached to the base of the ovary. In this arrangement, the ovules develop at the bottom part of the ovary, typically from a single point. This type of placentation is common in plants with a unilocular (single-chambered) ovary, such as in the families Asteraceae and Poaceae. Basal placentation can be advantageous in terms of structural support and nutrient distribution to the developing seeds.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The steps below are involved in the testing of a leaf for starch.  Study them carefully and answer this question  I. Decolorize leaf  II. Dip decolorized leaf in warm water  III. Place leaf in boiling water  IV. Add iodine solution    The correct order for the test is","images":[],"options":{"A":"I, II, III and IV","B":"I, III, II and IV","C":"II, III, I and IV","D":"III, I, II and IV"},"answer":"D","explanation":"To test for starch on leaf  III - Place leaf in boiling water  I - Decolorize leaf in Alcohol  II - Dip decolourized leaf in warm water  IV - Add iodine solution","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"The steps below are involved in the testing of a leaf for starch.  Study them carefully and answer this question  I. Decolorize leaf  II. Dip decolorized leaf in warm water  III. Place leaf in boiling water  IV. Add iodine solution  The best time to pluck the leaf for the experiment is","images":[],"options":{"A":"after being exposed to sunlight","B":"three hours after sunset","C":"before sunrise","D":"six hours after sunset"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The best time to pluck the leaf for the experiment is after being exposed to sunlight (option 1). This is because photosynthesis, the process by which plants produce starch, occurs during the day when the plant is exposed to sunlight. Therefore, the concentration of starch in the leaf will be highest after a period of sunlight exposure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The steps below are involved in the testing of a leaf for starch.  Study them carefully and answer this question  I. Decolorize leaf  II. Dip decolorized leaf in warm water  III. Place leaf in boiling water  IV. Add iodine solution  In which of the plant tissues are guard cells located?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Epidermis","B":"Mesophyll","C":"Vascular bundles","D":"Meristems"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Guard cells are located in the epidermis of the plant. They are specialized cells in the epidermis of leaves, stems and other organs that are used to control gas exchange. They are produced by the epidermis and form a small pore, or stoma, that allows for gas exchange. The other options, Mesophyll, Vascular bundles, and Meristems, are incorrect as they are not the location of guard cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"The association between two organisms in which one of the organisms gains and the other loses is referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"saprophytism","B":"commensalism","C":"mutualism","D":"parasitism"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Parasitism can be defined as an association between two whereby one is the host and the other is the parasite. In this type of association the one of the Organism (Parasites) gain while the other (Host) loses.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"The function of the villi in the alimentary canal is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"secrete gastric juice","B":"curdle milk","C":"emulsify fat","D":"increase the surface area for absorption"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The function of the villi in the alimentary canal is to increase the surface area for absorption. Villi are small, finger-like projections that extend into the lumen of the small intestine. They increase the internal surface area of the intestinal walls making available a greater surface area for absorption. Absorption is the process by which the products of digestion are absorbed into the bloodstream and lymphatic system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following structures is not an organ of the digestive system?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Oesophagus","B":"Pancreas","C":"Stomach","D":"Kidney"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The kidney is not an organ of the digestive system. The digestive system is made up of the gastrointestinal tract\u2014also called the digestive tract\u2014and the liver, pancreas, and gallbladder. The digestive system processes food, extracts and absorbs nutrients and water, and eliminates the leftovers as waste. The kidney, on the other hand, is part of the urinary system and its main function is to filter the blood and remove waste products and excess substances.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"The diagram below shows the effect of nitrates on water bodies.  Study it carefully and answer this question      The source of the nitrates in the part labeled I is the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"root nodules of legumes","B":"cloud","C":"fertilizers","D":"organic matter"},"answer":"C","explanation":"From the diagram, the source of the nitrate from part labelled I is the fertilizers.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"The diagram below shows the effect of nitrates on water bodies.  Study it carefully and answer this question    The phenomenon in the diagram is termed","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"denitrification","B":"conservation","C":"eutrophication","D":"global warming"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Eutrophication is characterized by excessive plant and algal growth due to increased availability of one or more limiting growth factors needed for the photosynthesis e.g nutrient fertilizers","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"The diagram below shows the effect of nitrates on water bodies.  Study it carefully and answer this question    Another cause that could lead to the phenomenon in the diagram is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"exhaust from cars","B":"oil spillage","C":"dumping of sewage","D":"excess rainfall"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Dumping of sewage in rivers can also helps to increase the bacteria in water bodies thereby reducing the oxygen level of the river.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"In ecology, a community refers to","images":[],"options":{"A":"a number of individuals of a given species","B":"groups of different organisms living in a habitat","C":"existing species in an abandoned farmland","D":"the dominant species in a habitat"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In ecology, a community is a group or association of populations of two or more different species occupying the same geographical area and in a particular time, also known as a biocoenosis. The term community has a variety of uses.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The direction of wind is determined by","images":[],"options":{"A":"an anemometer","B":"a secchi disc","C":"a wind vane","D":"a barometer"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The direction of wind is determined by a wind vane. An anemometer measures wind speed, a secchi disc is used to measure water transparency, and a barometer measures atmospheric pressure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Food webs are complex because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the number of producers are large","B":"many animals feed directly on producers","C":"they include primary, secondary and tertiary consumers","D":"some animals form part of several food chains"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Food webs are complex because they involve multiple interconnected food chains. An animal can be part of several food chains, meaning it can eat different types of food and be eaten by different types of animals. This creates a complex network of feeding relationships.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Special modifications which enable an organism to survive in its habitat is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"adaptation","B":"tolerance","C":"mimicry","D":"colouration"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Adaptation refers to the process where an organism undergoes modifications in its structure, function or behavior to better survive in its environment. These changes are usually a result of evolution and can be physical (like the development of webbed feet in aquatic animals) or behavioral (like nocturnal activity in desert animals to avoid daytime heat).","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"Which of the following relationships does not involve two organisms?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Commensalism","B":"Saprophytes","C":"Symbiosis","D":"Parasitism"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Saprophities does not involves two organisms. This is the process whereby organisms feed on dead or decaying substance , this form of feeding does not involve an association between organism.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"Overcrowding in a population does not result in","images":[],"options":{"A":"death","B":"commensalism","C":"competition","D":"migration"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Overcrowding in a population can lead to death, competition, and migration as resources become scarce and individuals compete for survival. However, commensalism, which is a type of relationship where one organism benefits while the other is neither harmed nor benefited, is not a direct result of overcrowding.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : PUBLIC HEALTH","question":"A pandemic is an outbreak of disease that","images":[],"options":{"A":"is confined to a town","B":"is widespread","C":"will not spread","D":"has limited spread"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A pandemic is an outbreak of a disease that occurs over a wide geographic area and affects an exceptionally high proportion of the population. Therefore, it is widespread, not confined to a town or has limited spread. It is also not correct to say it will not spread because by definition, a pandemic is a disease that is spreading.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"The rational and prudent use of natural resources is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"preservation","B":"conservation","C":"utilization","D":"management"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The rational and prudent use of natural resources is known as conservation. Preservation refers to the act of maintaining something in its original or existing state, while utilization simply means the act of using something. Management could be a broader term that includes conservation, but it also includes other aspects like distribution and control. Therefore, the most accurate term for the rational and prudent use of natural resources is conservation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Which of the following natural resources cannot be conserved?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Soil","B":"Water","C":"Wildlife","D":"Air"},"answer":"D","explanation":"All natural resources can be conserved. Conservation refers to the sustainable use and management of natural resources including wildlife, water, air, and earth deposits. However, the conservation of air is different from other resources because it is abundant and not subject to depletion in the same way as other resources. Therefore, while we can take measures to reduce air pollution, we cannot 'conserve' air in the traditional sense.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Which of the following actions support conservation? To","images":[],"options":{"A":"protect endangered species","B":"preserve trees for timber","C":"permit hunting activities","D":"provide income for the government"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Conservation involves actions that protect and preserve the natural environment. Protecting endangered species is a direct action that supports conservation. It involves implementing measures to prevent the extinction of species that are at risk. This can be achieved through various means such as creating wildlife reserves, implementing laws that protect endangered species, and promoting biodiversity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"A noticeable physical appearance of individuals of the same species is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"physical variation","B":"physiological variation","C":"morphological variation","D":"discontinuous variation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The noticeable physical appearance of individuals of the same species is called morphological variation. Morphological variation refers to the differences in the physical appearance and characteristics of individuals within the same species. This can include differences in size, shape, color, structure, etc.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"A blend of inherited and acquired characteristics shows","images":[],"options":{"A":"variation","B":"inheritance","C":"evolution","D":"heredity"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A blend of inherited and acquired characteristics shows variation. Variation refers to the differences in physical and genetic characteristics between individuals within the same species. These differences can be due to both inherited (genetic) factors and acquired (environmental) factors.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"A cross between two parent produced four offsprings with blood group AB, BB, BO and AO. What is the blood group of their parents?","images":[],"options":{"A":"AA and BO","B":"BB and AO","C":"AB and BO","D":"AB and AO"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The blood group of their parents are AB and BO. A cross between the two parent will result in AB, BB, BO and AO","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"A sick baby was successfully transfused with blood from the father who has blood group AB. What is the group of the sick baby?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A","B":"B","C":"AB","D":"O"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Donors with blood type A... can donate to recipients with blood types A and AB  Donors with blood type B... can donate to recipients with blood types B and AB  Donors with blood type AB... can donate to recipients with blood type AB only  Donors with blood type O... can donate to recipients with blood types A, B, AB and O","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"The illustration below represents a cross between a colour-blind male and a normal female.  Study it carefully and answer this question      What is the genotype ratio of carrier females to normal males in the cross?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"1:1","B":"2:3","C":"3:4","D":"4:1"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Genotypic ratio is 2 : 2  The genotype ratio of carrier females to normal males in the cross= 1 : 1","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"The illustration below represents a cross between a colour-blind male and a normal female.  Study it carefully and answer this question    Which of the genotypes are carriers of colour blindness?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I and II only","B":"I and III only","C":"II and III only","D":"I, II and III only"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The genotype are carrier of colour blindness is I & II.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Scientists who study genetics are known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"genealogists","B":"geneticist","C":"medalists","D":"gene scientists"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Scientists who study genetics are known as geneticists. Genetics is the study of genes, genetic variation, and heredity in organisms. A geneticist is a biologist who studies genetics, the science of genes, heredity, and variation of organisms.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following scientists did not contributes to the development of genetics?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Wilhem Johannsen","B":"Thomas Morgan","C":"Gregor Mendel","D":"Felix Durjadin"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Felix Durjadin is the only scientists from the option that do not contribute to the development of genetics. He contributed to the development of cell.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following terms is associated with natural selection?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Adaptive radiation","B":"Differential reproduction","C":"Population variability","D":"Survival of the fittest"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The term 'Survival of the fittest' is associated with natural selection. Natural selection is a process where organisms that are better adapted to their environment tend to survive and produce more offspring. The term 'Survival of the fittest' was coined by Herbert Spencer after reading Charles Darwin's theory of natural selection and it means that the organisms that are the most fit for their environment are the ones that will survive and reproduce.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"In which of the following insects is group instinct not displayed?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Soldier ants","B":"Cockroaches","C":"Honeybees","D":"Termites"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Group instinct is a type of social behavior displayed by certain animals, including insects, in which they work together in a way that benefits the group as a whole. Soldier ants, honeybees, and termites are known for their group instincts, where they work together for the survival of their colony. Cockroaches, on the other hand, do not display group instinct. They are generally solitary insects and do not work together in a group.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2016>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2016","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The inability of an organism to adapt to its habitat can lead to","images":[],"options":{"A":"dormancy","B":"adaptation","C":"extinction","D":"survival"},"answer":"C","explanation":"If an organism is unable to adapt to its habitat, it may not be able to survive in that environment. This could lead to the extinction of that species. Adaptation is the process by which an organism becomes better suited to its habitat. Dormancy is a period in an organism's life cycle when growth, development, and physical activity are temporarily stopped. Survival is the state of continuing to live or exist, typically in spite of an accident, ordeal, or difficult circumstances. Therefore, the inability to adapt can lead to extinction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];